description:
Even if you’re not in the Philippines, you can still make Laing with freshly pressed coconut milk. I just found out how to make one from scratch (thanks to @rajivsurendra video!) I bought a coconut scraper at an Indian grocery store (I’m sure you can also buy one online). I got the coconuts from an Asian grocery store (one fresh coconut can be equivalent to one can and a half of canned coconut milk). After scraping, I put the grated coconut and a little bit of boiling water in a blender and pureed it. I transferred to a strainer and pressed it with a spatula. You can also use your hands to squeeze the heck out of the coconut shreds. The cream coming out will get thinner over time (the first extract is the coconut cream, 
second is called the coconut milk). If you’re having a hard time pressing, keep adding boiling water 1/4 cup at a time to help extract. Now you have freshly squeezed coconut milk!

For the Laing recipe:

Ingredients:
3-5 tablespoons cooking oil 
5 cloves of garlic, minced 
1 medium onion, chopped 
2 tablespoons black bean garlic sauce
1-2 green chili pepper (remove the membrane and seeds if you don’t want spicy)
1 tablespoon organic brown sugar 
1 small package of nori snack, cut to strips
8 cups coconut milk (preferably freshly squeezed)
4 ounces dried taro leaves, cut into strips
Salt to taste 

In a medium to large pot, add oil, garlic, and onions. Cook over low heat until the onions have turned soft and clear.

Add the chili pepper, black bean garlic sauce, brown sugar, and nori seaweed.

Pour the coconut milk and gently mix in the taro leaves. 

Let it cook for 45 minutes to one hour, gently mixing every 15 minutes or so to make sure nothing sticks on the bottom of the pot. 

After about 45 minutes to an hour, taste and see if the taro is not itchy. If it is slightly, cook further for 20-30 more minutes. The leaves should be fully cooked and broken down and wilted. 

If you want it more savory, you can add salt or black bean garlic sauce. You can also add fried tofu or mushrooms or preferred meat alternative. 

Turn off the heat and serve hot with rice.
